<AbstractNarration>This program will develop new analysis methods for current and upcoming cosmological hydrogen 21cm intensity mapping data from the Tianlai experiment, located in a radio quiet area of Western China. Such mapping provides important clues to the evolution of gas and galaxies in the early universe. Broader impacts include training of undergraduate students and postdocs, and development of inexpensive radio telescopes at Fermilab and UW-Madison using new software-defined-radio techniques for use by high-school and college students, through the NSF/DOE QuarkNet program.&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;The experiment will measure the three dimensional large scale structure of the universe via hydrogen emission from distant galaxies. The primary goal is to develop ways to handle the large foreground signal, which has been previously quantified in a path-finder 21cm program conducted on NSF's Green Bank Telescope.</AbstractNarration>
